 Rally — Plain-English Build Plan                                                                                                                              ↑

 Context                                                                                                                                                       ↑

 rally-app currently has only a spec (CLAUDE.md) and a status tracker (PROGRESS.md) — no code has been written yet. Before scaffolding starts, you (the owner, not a developer) asked for a description of how the build will unfold: the stages, what tech is used at each step, what you'll actually be able to see/test, and what could go wrong. This document is that walkthrough, in plain language, based on the existing spec in CLAUDE.md.                                           ↑

   Nothing here changes the spec — it's a narrative version of the build order already agreed, for your own understanding and to sanity-check before work starts.↑

   Update during planning: the product framing has shifted to be solo-first. Rather than leading with "invite your group and everyone joins," v1 leads with one person entering everyone's location themselves on a single screen — which the spec already technically supports, since Screen 2's location boxes were never gated per-person. Two concrete changes from this:                                                                                                             ↑
   - The location cap rises from 4 to 6.
   - The share link stays in v1 (so a friend can still open the same session and tweak it if they want), but it's no longer the primary framing — it's an option,↑not a required step. The real-time "each person joins separately" collaborative flow stays parked in Phase 2, as already noted in the spec.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   This means CLAUDE.md will need two edits before/alongside Stage 6: bump MAX_LOCATIONS from 4 to 6 (affecting Screen 2, the session data model, and validation), and adjust Screen 1/2 copy to lead with "do it yourself" rather than "invite your group."                                                                     ↑

   ---                                                                                                                                                           ↑
   The shape of the app, in one paragraph
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   One person opens Rally and types in up to 6 places (postcodes or tube station/area names) — their own and their friends' — on a single screen, with an optional link to share if they want someone else to add or check it. The app works out the tube station that gives everyone the fairest journey — not the geographic middle, but the place where the longest journey for any one person is as short as possible. It then shows nearby pubs/cafes/restaurants near that station.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   ---
   Stage 1 — The skeleton (scaffolding)                                                                                                                          ↑

   What happens: Set up the basic Next.js project — the folders, the styling system, and a blank deployment on Vercel so there's a live URL from day one (even if↑it just says "Hello").
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Tech stack: Next.js (the web framework), TypeScript (a stricter version of JavaScript that catches mistakes early), Tailwind CSS (styling), Vercel (hosting).
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Outcome you'll see: A live, empty website at a Vercel URL. Nothing functional yet, but it proves the foundation works and is deployed.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Challenges: Low risk — this is routine setup. The only real decision is whether to point a custom domain (joinrally.place) at it now or later.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   ---
   Stage 2 — Turning words into map coordinates (geocoding)                                                                                                      ↑

   What happens: Build the logic that takes what someone types — "SW4 7AJ" or "Brixton" — and turns it into a precise latitude/longitude. Postcodes go through on↑ service (Postcodes.io), station/area names go through another (TfL's StopPoint Search), decided automatically by checking if the text looks like a postcode.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Tech stack: Postcodes.io (free postcode lookup), TfL StopPoint Search API (station/area name lookup), a small piece of custom logic to decide which one to use.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Outcome you'll see: Nothing visual yet — this is tested behind the scenes (e.g. feeding in "Clapham North" and confirming it returns the right coordinates).
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Challenges: Ambiguous input is the main risk — "Victoria" could mean the station or the area, and typos/partial names need sensible fallback behaviour (a clear error rather than a crash) rather than silently guessing wrong.                                                                                               ↑

   ---                                                                                                                                                           ↑
   Stage 3 — Getting real journey times (the risky core)
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   What happens: For every candidate meeting station, ask TfL's Journey Planner "how long would it take to get here from this person's location?" This is repeated for every person × every candidate, so the spec calls for two safeguards: caching results so the same journey isn't queried twice, and limiting how many requests fire at once (max 10 simultaneously) so TfL's API doesn't get overwhelmed or time out.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Open item — the candidate station list doesn't exist yet. The spec calls for "~30 stations across Zones 1–3" (roughly inner/central London's well-connected interchanges) as the set of places the app tests journey times against, but no actual list of station names/coordinates has been written. This is /lib/candidates.ts in the build order — it needs to be created as part of this stage, before journey times can be calculated against anything.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Tech stack: TfL Journey Planner API, Vercel KV (a fast cache that remembers recent journey times for 6 hours so repeat queries are instant).
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Outcome you'll see: Still behind-the-scenes, but this is the stage the spec explicitly flags as the one to prove works before building any screens — if TfL's data doesn't behave as expected, it changes everything downstream.                                                                                            ↑

   Challenges: This is the highest-risk stage. TfL's API is slow (1–2 seconds per call) and rate-limited, so with up to 6 people × ~30 stations that's up to 180 calls — without batching and caching, this would be slow or fail outright. There's also a chance some journeys simply have no good TfL route; the app needs to skip those candidates gracefully rather than breaking.                                                                                                        ↑

   ---                                                                                                                                                           ↑
   Stage 4 — The fairness algorithm
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   What happens: With everyone's journey time to every candidate station now known, this stage just does the maths: for each candidate, find the longest journey anyone would have, then pick the candidate where that longest journey is the shortest (this is what "minimax" means — minimize the maximum).                  ↑

   Tech stack: Plain TypeScript — no external services, pure logic.                                                                                              ↑

   Outcome you'll see: Still behind-the-scenes, but testable directly — feed in known journey times, confirm the "winning" station matches what you'd expect by hand.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Challenges: Low risk on its own since it's simple logic, but it's only as good as Stage 3's data — any gaps there (missing journeys, wrong coordinates) surface as wrong-looking results here.                                                                                                                                ↑

   ---                                                                                                                                                           ↑
   Stage 5 — Wiring it together (API routes)
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   What happens: Build the handful of behind-the-scenes endpoints the website calls: create a session, add a person's location, trigger the calculation, fetch nearby venues. This is the plumbing that connects what a user does on screen to the logic built in Stages 2–4.                                                ↑

   Tech stack: Next.js API routes, Vercel KV (storing session data for 24 hours), Google Places Nearby API (with its own 12-hour cache, same reasoning as Stage 3↑— slow and costs money at scale).
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Outcome you'll see: You can start testing real flows with tools like a browser or Postman — create a session, get an ID back, add locations, trigger a calculation, get a real result back as raw data (not yet styled).                                                                                             ↑

   Challenges: Keeping API keys (TfL, Google) secure server-side — never exposed to the browser — and handling the case where a session has expired or doesn't exist.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   ---
   Stage 6 — The screens people actually use                                                                                                                     ↑

   What happens: Build the three actual pages: the homepage (one button), the session page (up to 6 location boxes you fill in yourself, with an optional "share"↑link if you want someone else to add or check a location, then "Find Rally Point"), and the results page (winning station, map, journey times, venue suggestions).                                                                                                                                                 ↑

   Tech stack: React components, Tailwind CSS, Google Maps JS + Autocomplete (for the map display and location input).                                           ↑

   Outcome you'll see: The full real product — you can type in up to 6 places yourself and get a real result on your phone, or share the link first if you'd rath↑r someone else fill in their own spot.
                                                                                                                                                                 ↑
   Challenges: The calculation takes 5–15 seconds (all those TfL calls from Stage 3), so the loading state needs to feel intentional rather than broken. Everything also has to work well on a phone screen down to 375px wide, since that's how most people will actually use it in a group chat.                                ↑

   ---                                                                                                                                                           ↑
   After Stage 6
                                                                                                                                                               ↑
 Polish, real-world testing with actual friend groups, and fixing whatever breaks in practice — plus deciding on the visual style (palette/accent colour is still marked TBD in the spec).

 Once the solo flow is proven, the next graduation step (still Phase 2, not part of this build) is the real-time collaborative version: each person joins via the link and adds their own location rather than one person typing for everyone, plus accounts/persistent groups so a regular friend group doesn't have to re-enter locations each time. Venue voting and other cities remain parked further out.

